        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Two basebands will be used to record the [C I] (492.16GHz) and the CS (489.75 GHz) lines in the correlator upper side band. The lower side band contains the remaining two basebands, which are set to optimize the sensitivity in the continuum. 

We request to record [C I] and CS emission using two 937.5 MHz bands. Each band covers a velocity range of 571 km/sec and delivers a resolution of about 0.34 km/sec, after averaging every two channels. The channel averaging is adopted to lower the data rate. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request an angular resolution of 0.8 arcsec to match the resolution of the observation of H2 shown in Figure 3 [8]. This resolution can be obtained at Band 8 using the most compact array configuration C36-1, which delivers a synthesized beam FWHM of 0.7" and a maxinum recoverable scale of 5.5". Since this latter value is much smaller that the extent of the atomic and molecular line emission in Carina, ACA plus Total Power array observations are required to properly map the emission toward our source. 

Using the simobserve tool in CASA, we calculate that the combination of C36-1 12m atenna array, ACA, and TP observations would result in a synthesized beam FWHM of about 1" when natural weighting is adopted. A best solution would be perform the requested observations using the second most compact configuration C36-2, which would deliver a resolution of about 0.7" after the combination with ACA and TP data. 

We will map the proposed rectangular area of 30"X60" using a standard hexagonal mosaic pattern with pointings spaced by 0.511 X HPBW to sample the emission at the Nyquist spatial frequency. This results in 57 pointings for the 12m antenna array, and 22 pointings for ACA observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Mapping the Western Wall in [C I] is the primary focus of the proposed Band 8 observations. The width of the [C I] line in Carina is between 5-10 km/sec [11]. We base our sensitivity request on a channel with of 1 km/sec in order to spetrally resolve the line in 5-10 channels. This velocity resolution is required to kinematically separate different components of the West Wall and constrain the 3-dimensional distribution of the gas. 

The sensitivity resquest is based on the observed mean intensity of the C I line in Carina (about 6K) [11] and on the requirement to achive a peak signal-to-noise ratio of 20 in a 1 km/sec channel, to properly study the morphology of the emission. This corresponds to a noise level 
of 0.3 K. 


 

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
