        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The adopted correlator configuration is the standard configuration for mapping CO isotopologues in Band 6 proposed in the ALMA Technical Handbook. Each line will be recorded using a 117.188 MHz wide spectral band which delivers a velocity resolution of 80 m/s and a total velocity coverage of 152 km/s. Note that the adoption of larger bands would not allow to observe all the CO lines with a single spectral setup. Since the lines are two faint to be detected at the resultion of 80 m/s, the data will be spectrally averaged to a final velocity resolution of about 0.2 km/sec to reduce the data rate.  
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request an angular resolution of 0.8 arcsec to match the resolution of the [C I] and H2 map. 
This resolution can be achived at Band 6 using the array configuration C36-3, after combining with ACA and TP data as discussed in the case of [C I] mapping. 

We propose to map the CO emission across the same area of 30"X60" targeted by [C I] observations. 
This results in 13 pointings for the 12m antenna array, and 5 pointings for ACA observations, when Nyquist sampling is adopted. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Mapping the Western Wall in the 13CO J=2-1 line is the primary focus of the proposed Band 6 observations. The requested sensitivity is calculated, as in the case of [C I], based on a typical brightness temperature of the the 13CO line of 4 K (Figure 2) and on the requirement to detect the line at a signal-to-noise ratio of 20 in a 1 km/sec channel. This results in a required noise level of 0.2 K. 

The 12CO, 13CO, and C18O J=2-1 lines will be observed simultaneosly. The 12CO line is in average 10 times brighter than 13CO [5]. The proposed observations should therefore detect 12CO 2-1 with a signal-to-noise ratio of about 200. However, this line is found to be mostly optically thick and it is therefore a good tracer of the gas temperature but not of its density. The C18O J=2-1 line is in average 10 times fainter than 13CO, and might therefore be detected at low signal-to-noise.  
 


</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
